k markdown-new-styling"><p data-start=3D"0" data-end=3D"136">There are seve=
ral <strong data-start=3D"18" data-end=3D"42">types of hybrid cars</strong>=
, based on how the electric motor and gasoline engine work together. Here=
=E2=80=99s a clear breakdown:</p>
<h3 data-start=3D"138" data-end=3D"169">=F0=9F=94=8B <strong data-start=3D"=
145" data-end=3D"169">1. Full Hybrid (HEV)</strong></h3>
<ul data-start=3D"170" data-end=3D"362">
<li data-start=3D"170" data-end=3D"250">
<p data-start=3D"172" data-end=3D"250">Can run on <strong data-start=3D"183=
" data-end=3D"200">gasoline only</strong>, <strong data-start=3D"202" data-=
end=3D"219">electric only</strong>, or a <strong data-start=3D"226" data-en=
d=3D"241">combination</strong> of both.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"251" data-end=3D"318">
<p data-start=3D"253" data-end=3D"318">The car automatically switches modes=
 to maximize fuel efficiency.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"319" data-end=3D"362">
<p data-start=3D"321" data-end=3D"362">Examples: Toyota Prius (standard hyb=
rid).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start=3D"364" data-end=3D"388">=E2=9A=A1 <strong data-start=3D"370=
" data-end=3D"388">2. Mild Hybrid</strong></h3>
<ul data-start=3D"389" data-end=3D"601">
<li data-start=3D"389" data-end=3D"482">
<p data-start=3D"391" data-end=3D"482">The electric motor <strong data-star=
t=3D"410" data-end=3D"421">assists</strong> the gasoline engine but <strong=
 data-start=3D"446" data-end=3D"481">cannot power the car on its own</stron=
g>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"483" data-end=3D"545">
<p data-start=3D"485" data-end=3D"545">Helps improve fuel economy and smoot=
h start-stop operations.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"546" data-end=3D"601">
<p data-start=3D"548" data-end=3D"601">Often found in many modern compact a=
nd mid-size cars.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start=3D"603" data-end=3D"655">=F0=9F=94=8C <strong data-start=3D"=
610" data-end=3D"655">3. Plug-In Hybrid Electric Vehicle (PHEV)</strong></h=
3>
<ul data-start=3D"656" data-end=3D"851">
<li data-start=3D"656" data-end=3D"706">
<p data-start=3D"658" data-end=3D"706">Has a <strong data-start=3D"664" dat=
a-end=3D"682">larger battery</strong> than a standard hybrid.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"707" data-end=3D"780">
<p data-start=3D"709" data-end=3D"780">You can <strong data-start=3D"717" d=
ata-end=3D"741">plug it in to charge</strong> and drive more miles on elect=
ric only.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"781" data-end=3D"851">
<p data-start=3D"783" data-end=3D"851">After the electric range is used, it=
 operates like a regular hybrid.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start=3D"853" data-end=3D"880">=F0=9F=94=84 <strong data-start=3D"=
860" data-end=3D"880">4. Series Hybrid</strong></h3>
<ul data-start=3D"881" data-end=3D"1093">
<li data-start=3D"881" data-end=3D"942">
<p data-start=3D"883" data-end=3D"942">The gasoline engine <strong data-sta=
rt=3D"903" data-end=3D"941">does not directly power the wheels</strong>.</p=
>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"943" data-end=3D"1021">
<p data-start=3D"945" data-end=3D"1021">It only generates electricity for t=
he electric motor that drives the wheels.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"1022" data-end=3D"1093">
<p data-start=3D"1024" data-end=3D"1093">Less common in passenger cars; use=
d in some EV range-extender setups.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start=3D"1095" data-end=3D"1124">=F0=9F=94=81 <strong data-start=
=3D"1102" data-end=3D"1124">5. Parallel Hybrid</strong></h3>
<ul data-start=3D"1125" data-end=3D"1250">
<li data-start=3D"1125" data-end=3D"1205">
<p data-start=3D"1127" data-end=3D"1205">Both the gasoline engine and elect=
ric motor can <strong data-start=3D"1175" data-end=3D"1204">directly drive =
the wheels</strong>.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"1206" data-end=3D"1250">
<p data-start=3D"1208" data-end=3D"1250">Most typical design in many hybrid=
s today.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start=3D"1252" data-end=3D"1288">=F0=9F=A7=A0 <strong data-start=
=3D"1259" data-end=3D"1288">6. Series-Parallel Hybrid</strong></h3>
<ul data-start=3D"1289" data-end=3D"1415">
<li data-start=3D"1289" data-end=3D"1341">
<p data-start=3D"1291" data-end=3D"1341">Combines both series and parallel =
hybrid features.</p>
</li>
<li data-start=3D"1342" data-end=3D"1415">
<p data-start=3D"1344" data-end=3D"1415">Optimizes efficiency by choosing t=
he best mode based on speed and load.</p>
